<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-04-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-04-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="21" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Dodge</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-04-25"><hi rend="italic">April 25,
                                1904</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 347.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to send to you inclosed
                            herewith two copies (with English translations) of the neutrality
                            proclamation of the German Government relating to the war now in
                            progress between Russia and Japan, dated February 13, 1904.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">H. Percival
                            Dodge.</hi></signed></closer>
                        <frus:attachment>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure.—Translation.]</seg></opener>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">German Empire.—Proclamation.</hi></head>
                            <p>According to official declarations which have been made here by the
                                Imperial Russian Government and the Imperial Japanese Government, a
                                state of war now exists between Russia and Japan. This is hereby
                                proclaimed, with the further announcement that it is the duty of
                                everyone within the territory of the Empire and in the German
                                protectorates, as well as of Germans in foreign lands, to refrain
                                from all acts contrary to the neutrality of Germany.</p>
                            <p>Berlin, February 13, 1904.</p>
                            <p>The Imperial Chancellor,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Count von
                                Bülow.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </frus:attachment>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>